3. Designing missions.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

3.1 Introduction.

Once you have designed your mission maps, compiling the mission is easy.
This Hilt2ED program combines your map and text files, allows you to edit
the mission details (objective etc...) and edit the enemy/civilian strengths
and optional weapons.

The editor also allows you to edit Campaigns and the File List which are
detailed in the next section.

3.1.1 System requirements.

Hilt2ED needs an AGA Amiga. The reqtools.library needs to be in the LIBS:
directory as does the hii.library.

Like SCM4, an icon with white text usually needs a left mouse click and
beige text usually needs a right mouse click.

3.1.2 Files needed.

Before you can compile a mission you need the following files ready for use.

* A Graphics map file in SCM4 or RAW format

* An Object map file in SCM4 or RAW format

* A normal text file containg the mission briefing and the names of the
  enemies.
  
  The text file should have 22 lines of text. The first 16 lines are the
  mission briefing that will appear before the mission is played. The lines
  must be 59 letters long or less, any longer and the excess will be
  removed. The next 6 lines contain the names of the enemies/civilians and
  should be no longer than 15 letters. First is the name of the gun turret
  (eg. Gun Pod), the next three lines contain the names of enemies 1,2 and 3
  (eg. Terror Troop, Battle Mage, War Droid etc...) and the last two lines
  contain the names of the two civilians (eg. Colonist).
  It is important to press return and the end of the last line. It doesn't
  matter if the text is longer than 22 lines (only the top 22 lines will be
  used) but the editor will not accept less.
  
3.2 The HEAD INFO panel.

This is where the mission header information is entered and edited.

3.2.1 The icons.

3.2.1.1 OBJECTIVE will cycle through the available mission objectives as
detailed above (2.7.3).

3.2.1.2 VALUE OF x is a number ranging from 0 to 299 which indicates the
gfx map tile number to destroy/remove (Objective 1), the object code number
to pickup/remove from the object map (Objective 2) or the number of the
enemy/civilian to kill (Objective 5).

3.2.1.3 NUMBER OF ALLIES specifies the number of allies you want to play
this mission (1-6). Make sure that there are at least the correct amount of
allied starts in the object map. This value is ignored if the mission is
part of a campaign.

3.2.1.4 FREE PASS KEYS ? when lit will give all allies free pass keys.
A message will also appear on the briefing screen too.

3.2.1.5 DEATHS END GAME ? when lit will not allow civilian casualties, if a
civilian should die then the mission will fail. A message will also appear
on the briefing screen.

3.2.1.6 NO EQUIP SCREEN ? when lit the equip screen will not appear and
players will start with no equipment. This is ignored if the mission is part
of a campaign.

3.2.1.7 CPU ENEMIES OFF ? applies only to random maps. When lit no enemies
will appear on the map. It is really intended to allow two player games with
random maps but without any enemies shooting at both sides.

3.2.1.8 KEEP OBJECTS ? applies only to campaign missions with objective 2
(pick up objects). By default, any objects picked up will be automatically
discarded at the end of each mission to avoid players having lots of objects
which may be completely useless. If lit, players will keep the objects and
start with them as normal on the next mission.

3.3 The FILES panel.

This is where you load the files to compile the mission and save out the
final file. The four lights on the left of the panel indicate when some data
(the text, maps and the graphics palette) have been loaded.

3.3.1 The Icons

3.3.1.2 IMPORT TEXT will ask for the mission briefing text file (see 3.1.2
for more information)

3.3.1.3 LOAD MISSION will ask for the filename of a finished Hilt II mission
from the mission disk. This means that you may look at the completed
missions and edit them or see how they are put together. Note that old Hilt
II missions (any version before this one) cannot be loaded.

3.3.1.4 LOAD RAW GFX MAP will ask for a RAW map file for the gfx map. This
file is 20000 bytes for a custom map and 3400 bytes for a random map. Other
sizes are not permitted. When loaded, the map will be displayed in the
centre of the screen. Random maps are put together randomly to give an idea
of how they will look.

3.3.1.5 LOAD SCM4 GFX MAP will ask for an SCM4 map file for the gfx map.
Because SCM4 files aslo include the graphic tiles used to design the map,
the palette within the file is also used and the enemies from the graphics
set are displayed in the top left of the screen.

3.3.1.6 LOAD RAW OBJ MAP will ask for a raw object map which must be the
same size as the gfx map. Object info is not displayed on the centre map.

3.3.1.7 LOAD SCM4 OBJ MAP will ask for an SCM4 object map file. The palette
and graphic tile data within the file is ignored.

3.3.1.8 LOAD IFF PALETTE will ask for a standard IFF palette (as saved out
by PPaint or DPaint) or picture with 32 colours. The 32 colours are used as
the mission palette. Each mission may have a palette that is different from
the one actually used in its graphics, this way you can tint the whole level
red or darken the colours for a night time effect. If you select a picture
the graphics are ignored, only the colours are used.

3.3.1.9 LOAD IFF GFX will ask for the IFF block graphics used to map the
mission. The palette is extracted and used as the colours for the map and
also the enemy graphics are displayed in the top right of the screen.

3.3.1.10 GFX SET is the number of the graphics block set that was used to
map the mission. This number must be correct so that Hilt 2 knows what
graphics set to load before the mission is played. This number can be 00-99
but currently only sets 00-08 have been designed. You can design your own
graphics sets, details in the Advanced Design section (section 5).

3.3.1.11 SAVE MISSION will pack and save the final mission to the mission
disk. The filename should be less that 16 characters.

3.4 The ENEMY INFO panel.

Enemy and civilian strengths and weaknessess are edited here.

3.4.1 The Icons

3.4.1.1 ENEMY NUMBER is the unit to edit. Enemy 1 is the gun turret, numbers
2,3 and 4 are enemies 1,2 and 3 and enemy numbers 5 and 6 are civilians.
This is the same number as used when setting mission objective 5 (see
3.2.1.2)

3.4.1.2 GUN is the optional weapon of the unit. If zero then a random weapon
is assigned. If a gun then all of those enemies will have that particular
gun and still might have armour and/or a grenade. If a hand to hand attack
weapon, all enemies will have that particular weapon. When enemies are given
hand to hand weapons, their behaviour changes and they head towards the
players more intelligently. Civilians cannot be armed.

3.4.1.3 ENERGY represents the energy (lifeforce) of the unit. This value is
also randomized +/-10 units by Hilt 2 so two identical enemies can have
different energies. The average value is 35.

3.4.1.4 SHOT SKILL represents the shot skill of the unit and therefore a
percentage of a hit using an aimed shot. This is randomized by +/-5 units.
The average value is 75.

3.4.1.5 DEFENCE FACTOR represents the percentage likelihood of a deflected
shot (and no damage). This can range from 0-10%. The average value is 2.

3.4.1.6 VISION RANGE represents the visual range of the enemy. Enemies can
only shoot at a target that they can see. The average is 10, the same as the
allies visual range.

3.4.1.7 ANGER represents the aggression of the unit. In short this is a
percentage value that indicates the probablility of the unit firing if able
to do so. So an Anger of 100 will make the enemy shoot at an ally whenever
they are able and never decide to move away. It is not a good idea to have
Anger too high though because often the enemy think that they can hit an
ally when they cannot and it might make the enemy more formidable if they
fired once or twice then moved away. Note also that when an enemy gets hit
their Anger increases by 5. The average value is 70.

3.4.1.8 MAX AP'S represents the units Action Points. Remember that civilians
cannot fire so do not need half as many Action Points as a combat unit. Gun
Turrets cannot move and must use all of their points firing, also this means
that turrets always reserve all of their AP's for opportunity fire and this
coupled with their all round vision makes them a difficult enemy.
Reducing the number of AP's an enemy has (particularly with hand to hand
attack aliens) will make the enemy easier the beat. The average value is 80,
the same as the value for allies.

3.5 The LISTS panel.

Detailed in the next section.

