4. Campaigns and the File List.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

4.1 Introduction.

The File List is like a directory listing that resides on your mission disk.
It contians the names of all of the character sets, missions and campaigns
on the disk and is used by Hilt 2 when the mission select screen appears. If
you add a mission to the mission disk, you must also make sure that its
filename is in the File List so that it appears on Hilt 2's mission select
screen. The filename for the File List is always HiltII-Missions.

Campaign files are essentially lists of the missions in the campaign. The
only other information they contain concerns the number of allies in the
campaign and when (and if) they visit the equip screen for supplies.
The filename for a campaign file is the campaign name that appears on the
mission select screen.

4.2 The LISTS panel.

4.2.1 Information shown.

The map in the centre of the screen now gets replaced by some text boxes.
The box on the left represents the current contents of the File List and the
box on the right shown the current contents of the Campaign being edited.

There are two groups of icons. The top ones allow the editing of the File
List and the ones below that allow the editing of the Campaign file.

4.2.2 Icons for editing the File List.

4.2.2.1 CLEAR LIST will blank the current file list to start again from
scratch.

4.2.2.2 LOAD LIST will pop up a file requestor to allow the loading of a
Fike List from the Mission Disk. The filename is HiltII-Missions although
this can be changed if saevd out under a different name.

4.2.2.3 SAVE LIST allows you to save the current file list. You can save
under any name but on the Mission Disk the name must be HiltII-Missions for
Hilt 2 to recognise the list.

4.2.2.4 ADD CHAR allows you to add a chracter file. A file requestor will
appear to allow you to select the character file to add. Note that only the
file requestor filename text is used, the character file doesn't even have
to exist. A Right Click on ADD CHAR will delete the last character file from
the File List. This applies to ADD MISSN and ADD CAMPN too.

4.2.2.5 ADD MISSN. As above but allows you to add a mission file. Remember
all of the missions, campaigns and character files present on the Mission
Disk but be in the file list. The maximum size of the filenames for
missions, campaigns or character files if 15 letters.

4.2.2.6 ADD CAMPN. As above but for adding a campaign file.

4.2.3 Icons for editing Campaign files.

4.2.3.1 CLEAR CAMPN will blank and initialise the current campaign file.

4.2.3.2 LOAD CAMPN will pop up a file requestor to allow the loading of a
campaign file.

4.2.3.3 SAVE CAMPN allows the saving of a campaign file. The file name is
the name of the campaign and should have a maximum size of 15 letters.

4.2.3.4 ADD MISSN allows you to add a mission to the camapign. Campaigns are
just lists of missions that are played one after another. It is reccomended
that when designing missions for a campaign that the mission filename in the
campaign are the same as ther camapign but followed by a number indicating
the order that they are played. For example Terrorist1, Terrorist2 etc...

4.2.3.5 NUM OF ALLIES is the number of allies used in the campaign. This
overrides the number in the actual mission file. As in missions make sure
that the number of starts present in the map is not less than the number of
allies set here.

4.2.3.6 VISIT EQUIP SCREEN AFTER MISSION indicates when the equip screen
will appear during a campaign. 00 here would mean that the players visit
the equip screen just before the first mission (just after the briefing). A
value of 16 here would mean that the players never visit the equip screen
and must complete the campaign entirely with weapons found on the mission
maps.

4.3 Examples.

You may load the HiltII-Mission file from the enclosed mission disk as an
example of a file list and also load in a campaign file (Eg. Tutorial) as an
example Campaign file.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

5. Advanced Design

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

5.1 Introduction.

This section describes how to make mission maps that start with fire already
burning on them or add power/ammo to objects that appear in the object maps.
Some objects (eg. powered computers) must have power and cannot be recharged
so this information is very useful.

Also here are details of drawing/designing your own gfx sets for Hilt II so
you can play using your own graphics.

5.2 Power/Fire - Edit Bit.

A knowledge of binary arithmetic is needed to add fire or power to Hilt II
maps.

The EDIT BIT icon is used to add power or fire to maps. When clicked on, the
map screen will turn into a bitplane display, showing each tile one bit at a
time as a pattern of black and white tiles indicating the 0's and 1's. A
Right Click on EDIT BIT will allow you to step through each bit (0-15) and
see the contents of the map.

While in edit bit mode, a Left Click will place a 1 in the bit map and a
Right Click will place a 0.

5.2.1 Adding fire to the gfx map.

Information of the strength of the fire is stored in bits 15-13 of the
graphics map blocks. Intensity is a number from 0-7, where 0 is no fire and
7 is the strongest fire. So for a fire of intensity of 6, set bit 15, bit 14
but not bit 13 of the block where you want the fire to appear because the
binary for 6 is %110.

When you exit edit bit mode after editing, the graphic block you just edited
will appear corrupt or different. Do not panic, Hilt 2 will display the
block correctly as you edited it beacuse it masks out the useful bits of the
block.

Just save out the RAW or SCM4 map as normal now. When the mission is
compiled and played, the squares you edited will start as on fire and
continue to spread/burn as normal.

5.2.2 Adding power/ammo to weapons/armour/computers.

Information on the power in the pickup is stored in bits 8-15 of the object
map. So if you wanted to map a Power Rifle with 75 shots for example you
would convert 75 to binary (01001011) and set each bit in the appropriate
bit planes, set bit 8, set bit 9, leave bit 10, set bit 11, leave bits 12
and 13, set bit 14 and leave bit 15.
Make sure you add power to the square where the pickup is located, noting
the coordinates to edit might be useful.

As above, when you turn off edit bit mode, the square containing the pickup
will look different but don't worry. Hilt 2 will mask out the power from the
pickup. The square will look fine in the main game.

You can put up to 255 power in any object but it is reccomended that you
keep to the maximum ammo/power ratings as listed in the object list.

Shield Units must have a power of one to work. A power of two will NOT make
the shield withstand two hits. Armour with no energy will not work.

Grenades, keys, hand 2 hand weapons and other pickups need no power. Don't
give them any or unpredictable things may happen. The only items that need
power are guns, armour and powered computers (object numbers 77-87).

Powered Computers need power too. In their case each power unit represents
one turn. The reccomended power is written in square brackets [] after their
name in the object list (Appendix B).

5.3 Designing Graphics Sets

With a program like Personal Paint or DPaint you can design your own
graphics sets for use with HiltII. A list of each graphic block is included
in Appendix C and if you use the current graphics sets in the Tiles 
directory for reference you can draw your own sets quite easily.

5.3.1 Guidelines

* The graphic mode is lo-res in 32 colours. You must keep some of the
  colours the same so that the allies etc.. still look okay.
  Load in a current graphics set. Colours 0,1 and 15-31 must stay the same.
  You can edit any of the remaining 13 colours.
  
* The palette is non-AGA resolution. It is reccomended that AGA users boot
  with original chips so that colour spreads look okay. If not then the
  colours you draw with will look different in Hilt II that when you are
  drawing the graphics.
  
* Refer to the block list. Note which objects cannot be walked or seen past
  and make them look like they can't to a player who has not seen the block
  list. Make the terminals recognisable and the inflammable barrels look
  inflammable. Make the centre square of the large crater look okay when it
  is tiles alone on the screen because after multiple hits floors/walls
  eventually become this square.
  
* Design interesting enemies. Black is transparent when designing the
  enemies. Keep the radar blip the same as the other graphics sets so
  players don't get confused when playing.
  
5.3.2 Using your graphics

You can load yor graphics set directly into SCM4 for editing your own maps
but also you need to convert the graphics into a raw format that Hilt II can
load during the game. This is easy, there is an icon to do this in SCM4.

Left Click on SAVE GX RAW on the Files Panel. A file requestor will pop up.
The filename must be H2-Levelxx.gfx where the xx is a number from 00-99.
This file must then be copied into the 'data' directory on the Mission Disk.
The number you entered in the filename is then the GFX SET NUMBER that is
specified on the Files Panel of the Hilt2ED Editor. The raw graphics file
size should be 55680 bytes.

